        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> why?\r\n\r\nthe majority of the api functions have `opts` as their last argument (don't know if any `vim.api.*` function doesn't and also e.g. `vim.fs.*` do)\r\n\r\nI think the `callback` last argument isn't strong enough here\r\nin the docs it says\r\n>- Any function signature that accepts a callback function should define the\r\n  callback as the LAST parameter, if possible. This improves readability of\r\n  calls by placing the less \"noisy\" arguments near the start. >\r\n    GOOD:\r\n    filter(table, opts, function() … end)\r\n    BAD:\r\n    filter(function() … end, table, opts)\r\n\r\nimo the big difference here and there is that the callback there is obviously bad because the thing it operates on is after it\r\nhere I think the readability is better as it is now\r\nthe `opts` table has many different options which are less important to see what the thing does. They just \"modify\" the action (e.g. expr or buffer). The table can also be quite big and be way more noisy than a callback like `vim.lsp.buf.references`. You must also consider that often the callback is just a function like in the example I just gave (without `function() ... end`) or just a string (also regarding https://github.com/nvim-neorocks/nvim-best-practices where people are encouraged to use `<Plug>` mappings)\r\nthat would result in not really readable function signatures like `vim.keymap.set(\"n\",\"gc\",{buffer=true,desc=\"Toggle comment on current line\"}, \"<Plug>CommentToggleLine\"\r\nAlso I personally really don't like `nil` arguments if a user doesn't want any opts even though that's never \"required\" because it's an overload it's kinda confusing having two different signatures\r\n\r\nlast but not least\r\nthe `vim.api.nvim_set_keymap` function and also the old vimscript mappings always have `lhs` and `rhs` right next to each other and after each others and users are used to this",
