        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> the majority of the api functions have `opts` as their last argument\r\n\r\nThat is simply a limitation of the API, which does not support variable \"arity\" of function signatures.\r\n\r\n> The table can also be quite big and be way more noisy\r\n\r\nAll kinds of things are possible. Speculating about this makes it impossible to predict anything as a user, so it's better to have a consistent guideline. Options can be verbose sometimes, but the function is *always* present.\r\n\r\n> the `vim.api.nvim_set_keymap` function \r\n\r\nAPI is a low-level extension point for exposing internals. It's irrelevant for Lua which is a high-level interface intended to be maximally ergonomic.\r\n\r\n> and also the old vimscript mappings always have `lhs` and `rhs` right next to each other and after each others and users are used to this\r\n\r\nThe vimscript mappings provide all \"options\" before the RHS. If we want to match that, the signature would be:\r\n\r\n    set(..., lhs, rhs)\r\n\r\nBut I don't think that's necessary, because as a function call, LHS is visually what one looks for, so it's useful for it to be near the start.",
